✨FEATURE | Show us your collections!!✨

Happy #collectabeautifullife Friday! This week I am so excited to be featured! 

Here’s a little bit you may not know about me. My middle name is Fabiana, and although friends know me as Fabiana, most people call me by my first name Claudia!

In 2011 I started my blog Ciao Newport Beach. I was born in Buenos Aires and grew up in a family greatly influenced by Argentine-Italian traditions, so I combined the Italian greeting “Ciao” and the town I live in “Newport Beach” to create the name of my blog where I love to share my favorite tablescapes, decorating tips, recipes, gardening ideas, and fun vintage collections. I also love to combine treasured heirlooms and flea market finds with modern coastal furnishings. 

My favorite blog posts are those that feature unique tablescapes which combine new and vintage tableware in a contrasting way. I also enjoy hunting for fun collectables at flea markets and thrift stores. My home in the coastal town of Newport Beach has become a creative sanctuary. 

To join in the fun and have a chance to be featured as a guest host follow all our accounts below and use #collectabeautifullife to show us YOUR collections… we can’t wait to see them! New features will be posted every Friday. Make sure you tag a friend who loves to collect too!

I just found this fun domino garland that I made last year in one of my Christmas boxes, and I have to say it’s one of my favorite DIY Christmas projects of all time!
 
These vintage black dominoes are the perfect element to put together a unique and fun holiday garland. I simply drilled the vintage dominoes through the long way so I could string them with wood beads. I painted the larger wooden beads with a red chalk paint wash and used fishing line to string it all together. Strung up in domino order too! It turned out a lot cuter than I thought!

You may have spotted them in last year’s Christmas issue of @countrysamplerfarmhousestyle . Swipe to see more details.

Here’s one of my favorite ways to create an easy and festive gift wrap for smaller Christmas presents. All you need to start is some brown craft paper and a sewing machine. 

Here’s how it all came together: I cut brown kraft paper to form large envelopes, and then I use white thread to sew up the edges. It’s easier to create the envelope first, and then put the gift inside (but I did it both ways). I used Christmas rubber stamps (with white paint) to embellish the packages with more holiday detail.
 
Once the gift is in the package, holes can be punched to insert ribbon near the top to tie off with a pretty bow or knot. In this instance, a red plaid scarf is ready to be enclosed in its own little package.

From the 2020 special Christmas issue of @countrysamplerfarmhousestyle

Since January, this brand-new garden has kept me busy every single day. We call it the new Potager Garden. This area has always been a small lawn, and over the years has had a swing set, baby pools and lots of children’s play equipment out here, but my love for growing veggies has now been fulfilled by this new veg garden. It’s such a dream come true, and just so happens to be the perfect spot for the raised beds, as the borders surrounding this area is a small orchard of sorts, filled with apple, lemon, orange, guava, plum and apricot trees.

It’s been a labor of love, for sure. Hours of sifting soil and compost, planting seedlings and bringing in tons of gravel have paid off with veggies starting to make their way into the kitchen. Our favorite new recipe is for a Swiss Chard Bruschetta. Freshly picked chard, sautéed with onions tops off a crispy piece of sourdough with just a flourish of cream cheese. It’s the perfect late breakfast snack that can’t be beat!

What I’m really looking forward to are summer tomatoes!! I’m also attempting to grow peppers and cucumbers again this year, for instant gazpacho fixings all summer long!  I’ve already planted several favorite tomatoes from @armstronggarden like Sun Gold, Costoluto Genovese, Principe Borghese, Box Car Willie and a few other tasty heirlooms.

But for now, I'll just be thinking of those tomatoes, while watching apple blossoms flutter in the wind. They’re just so pretty and put a big smile on my face!

🍏Happy Saturday! How about kicking off your weekend with a refreshing and delicious twist on a classic cocktail: Apple Sangria! This recipe is actually a “mocktail”, so it can be enjoyed by people of all ages. 

🍏This gorgeous pitcher from @vagabondhouse comes to life when it’s filled with these 4 simple ingredients: Apple Juice, Lemon Juice, Orange Juice, and Sparking White Grape Juice, and then add pretty sliced fruit. A simple and yummy recipe from @MarthaStewart.
.
.

🍏 Apple Sangria

·       2 quarts fresh apple juice, plus 1 apple thinly sliced 
·       1 cup fresh lemon juice (from 6 lemons) plus 1 lemon, thinly sliced
·       1 quart fresh orange juice (from 10 oranges) plus 1 orange, thinly sliced
·       1 bottle (24 ½ ounces) sparkling white-grape juice chilled

🍏 In a pitcher, combine the apple and lemon juices immediately after juicing. Stir in orange juice; cover, and chill. Just before serving, add grape juice and sliced fruit.

I just found out the best secret for growing paperwhites! To keep them from growing too tall and leggy, add a bit of rubbing alcohol or vodka to the water in your watering can when you water them. 

Also called "Drunken Paperwhites", the ratio is 7 parts water to 1 part alcohol, and it really works! I found out about this hack from Kirk at my local @armstronggarden when I bought these bulbs two weeks ago. The result will be shorter stems and a more proportionate appearance.
